## 2. Fossil Fuel Combustion: The Largest Contributor

Fossil fuel burning for electricity, transportation, and industry is the largest single source of global GHG emissions.

| Sector                  | % of Global GHG Emissions | Major Activities                        |
|-------------------------|---------------------------|---------------------------------------|
| Electricity Production  | ~20%                      | Coal, oil, natural gas combustion     |
| Transportation         | ~14%                      | Gasoline and diesel vehicle emissions |
| Industrial Processes   | ~11%                      | Extraction, refining, cement production |

The combustion process releases stored carbon as CO₂, significantly increasing atmospheric concentrations. Additionally, fossil fuel extraction releases methane through leaks, further exacerbating warming ([West, 2018](https://www.nationalgeographic.com/environment/article/how-do-humans-contribute-to-global-warming)).

---

## 3. Deforestation and Land-Use Changes

### 3.1 Carbon Release and Loss of Carbon Sinks

Forests act as vital carbon sinks, absorbing about 25% of human-generated CO₂ annually. Deforestation and land clearing for agriculture or urban development convert these sinks into sources of emissions.

- Clearing forests releases stored carbon in trees and soils as CO₂.
- Loss of forest area reduces the planet's capacity to absorb future emissions.

### 3.2 Scale of Impact

- Tropical deforestation accounts for approximately 10% of global greenhouse gas emissions, equivalent to about 3.0 billion tons of CO₂ annually ([Union of Concerned Scientists, 2013](https://www.ucsusa.org/resources/measuring-role-deforestation-global-warming)).
- Protecting and restoring forests could reduce global emissions by 18% by 2030, a mitigation potential comparable to eliminating fossil fuel use ([Milman, 2018](https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2018/oct/04/scientists-say-halting-deforestation-just-as-urgent-as-reducing-emissions)).

---

## 4. Agriculture and Animal Husbandry

### 4.1 Methane and Nitrous Oxide Emissions

Agriculture contributes significantly to global warming through:

- **Methane:** Produced by enteric fermentation in ruminant livestock (cows, sheep), accounting for about 40% of agricultural emissions.
- **Nitrous Oxide:** Emitted from fertilizers and manure, with a GWP 298 times that of CO₂.

### 4.2 Resource Use and Environmental Degradation

- Agriculture uses about 70% of the world's freshwater resources, with animal agriculture being particularly resource-intensive ([Planète Énergies, 2017](https://www.planete-energies.com/en/medias/close/agriculture-impact-global-warming)).
- Land clearing for feed crops contributes to deforestation and habitat loss.
- Runoff from fertilizers and manure causes water pollution and dead zones in aquatic ecosystems ([Meek, 2019](https://www.onegreenplanet.org/environment/agriculture-and-climate-change-environmental-impact-of-factory-farming/)).

---

## 5. Scientific Consensus on Human-Caused Climate Change

A comprehensive survey of 88,125 climate-related peer-reviewed studies found that over 99.9% agree that human activities are the primary cause of recent global warming ([Lynas et al., 2021](https://iopscience.iop.org/article/10.1088/1748-9326/ac2966)).

| Year Range           | Consensus Percentage | Number of Papers Reviewed |
|----------------------|----------------------|---------------------------|
| 1991-2012            | 97%                  | ~12,000                   |
| 2012-2020            | >99.9%               | 88,125                    |

This overwhelming consensus underscores the reliability and robustness of the scientific understanding of anthropogenic climate change.

---

## 6. Feedback Loops and Future Projections

### 6.1 Permafrost Thawing

Warming in Arctic regions leads to permafrost thaw, releasing stored methane and CO₂, creating a feedback loop that accelerates warming ([West, 2018](https://www.nationalgeographic.com/environment/article/how-do-humans-contribute-to-global-warming)).

### 6.2 Climate Models and Temperature Trends

Climate models incorporating human GHG emissions accurately reproduce observed warming trends, whereas models considering only natural factors fail to do so ([West, 2018](https://www.nationalgeographic.com/environment/article/how-do-humans-contribute-to-global-warming)).

---

## Conclusion and Opinion

The evidence presented unequivocally demonstrates that human activities are the dominant cause of recent global warming. The combustion of fossil fuels, deforestation, and industrial agriculture have significantly increased atmospheric greenhouse gas concentrations, disrupting Earth's climate system. The scientific consensus is robust, with over 99.9% of peer-reviewed studies affirming anthropogenic climate change.

Given the scale and urgency of the problem, mitigating global warming requires immediate and sustained efforts to reduce emissions across all sectors, protect and restore forests, and transition to sustainable agricultural practices. Failure to address these drivers will exacerbate climate impacts, threatening ecosystems, human health, and global stability.

In my considered opinion, halting deforestation and transforming agricultural systems are as critical as decarbonizing energy production. These combined strategies offer the most comprehensive path to stabilizing the climate and safeguarding planetary health.

